Introduction:

This is a generated document for the Basher area. The public data available on property tax by parcel from March 2016 was joined with the geographical parcel data for the Anchorage area. Then for this report, filtered for only parcels within the borders of Basher community council.

This document was created as a demostartion during the 2016 rezoning process by Alaska Statistical Automation. If you have a project that might be an interesting project I would love to hear about it. Email me at hans.thompson1@gmail.com. Im located in downtown Anchorage.

This document is provided for fun only and should not be used for investment decisions. If you would like to use this data for a futher analysis of investment opportunities, please get in contact! (hans.thompson1@gmail.com)

If you feel there is an interesting visualization that could be done with this information that could add to this report please let me know and I would be happy to try and include it across all community councils.

Summary:

The Basher area contains 252 residential parcels and 4 non residential parcels. The total taxable residential value of land is $50,468,500 and the total taxable building value is $81,754,300.
The median taxable value for land and structures is $560,650

Parcel History and Value Exploration:


This chart is the total counts of individual parcels by zone within the community council borders. You can see the zoning definitions HERE.



Its interesting to see in each community council the taxable building value and if it coorelates or clusters in relation to land value. Sometimes the clustering can be in one and not the other. Planned residential construction can cluster value around building value if they are from the same construction plan. Areas where land ammenities are uniform can have clusters around taxed land value. Outliers have been removed greater than two standard deviations from the average.




Anchorage has had periods of time when construction has boomed and busted. At the community council level, there is a limited amount of land. Some communities have seen most of the constuction occur before the pipeline started construction was put in while others occured recently.
